sec.p:
The loads acting on the cylinder result from:


the influence of fibers on the teeth of card wire during the carding process; the forces are small and are omitted when calculating deflection of the cylinder shell;

the construction dead weight and the centrifugal force; their influence on the cylinder deflection may also be neglected due to the large stiffness of the shell and reinforcement rings, as well as the small rotational speed of the cylinder (circa 100–200 rpm); taking into account the dead weight and the centrifugal force makes a difference in deflection of no more than 3%;

reeling at tension of the metallic card wire.

In order to determine optimal dimensions of the cylinder, as presented in Figure 9, the following optimization task was solved:


the dimensions shown in Figure 10 were accepted as decision variables: g1, g2, b, c, h, s, t, d, D;

the deflection amplitude of cylinder Δ→min is the objective function for the task (see Figure 9);

the feasible set of the solution (constructional variants) is delimited by the following conditions:


○ m∧≤m0, that is, the mass of the optimal cylinder, should not exceed the initial mass that corresponds to the dimensions – decision variables assumed from the design documentation;

○ σred≤k, that is, the reduced stresses at any place of the construction, should not exceed the permissible stresses (steel S235JR7).


Figure 10.
Denotations of decision variables in optimization task.

The optimal structural form (bottoms) and optimal cylinder dimensions were determined assuming zero manufacturing tolerance of all cylinder dimensions. Industrial practice and experimental studies2 show that the shell deflection is mainly influenced by:


deviation of the wall thickness of the shell, g1;

deviations of the shell shape, which are measured by the cylinder radial run-out around its axis of rotation.
